<title>Nemzet 1996.07.06</title><BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000"><h1>Nemzet 1996.07.06</h1><!-- body="start" --><pre>N     N  EEEEEEE  M     M  ZZZZZZZ  EEEEEEE  TTTTTTTNN    N  E        MM   MM       Z   E           TN N   N  E        M M M M      Z    E           TN  N  N  EEEE     M  M  M     Z     EEEE        TN   N N  E        M     M    Z      E           TN    NN  E        M     M   Z       E           TN     N  EEEEEEE  M     M  ZZZZZZZ  EEEEEEE     T--->> M A G Y A R   I N T E R N E T   V I L A G L A P <<---<br></pre><h3>==<br><br>Alkotmanyos monarchia <br>[Magyar Narancs, #72]<br><br>[A "Magyar Narancs nevu szelsoliberalis szennylap alabbi <br>SZERKESZTOI cikket annak bemutatasaul kozoljuk, hogy (a) honnan <br>szarmazik a magyar politikai elet alpari stilusa (b) mennyire megveti <br>az SZDSZ azt a bunko kommunista munkasor MSZPt melynek <br>kiszolgalasara csakis olyan alliberalis gerinctelen fergek vetemednek, <br>mint ok. A magyar valosag kulonosen a politika immar egy olyan <br>mocsarba zullott, amelyet csakis azert erdemes dagasztani, hogy <br>testkozelbol HAJSZALPONTOSAN lehessen tudni hogy az <br>elkerulhetetlen feregirtaskor es a dogkeselyuk eltavolitasakor <br>KIKTOL is kell legelsokent megszabaditani ezt a szerencsetlen <br>nemzetet - a szerk]<br><br><br>Nyar van, alacsonyan szall a Baja Feri. Azt mondja peldaul A Het <br>kamerajaba, hogy azon a bizonyos botranyos napon, amikor a <br>kormany hulyet csinalt sajat frakciojabol (es a teljes magyar <br>torvenyhozasbol), o azert tartozkodott az uj alkotmany <br>koncepciojanak megszavazasatol, mert hianyzik belole a biodiverzitas <br>helyessegenek kimondasa, tehat a fajok sokfelesegenek elismerese. A <br>lelkiismerete alapjan szavazott mindenki, es nincs alkotmanyozasi <br>kenyszer<br><br>tette hozza olyan kenyszeredett, rossz lelkiismeretu felmosollyal, <br>mint aki rosszul szelektalta a kommunalis hulladekot. Az allat es <br>novenyvilag faji sokfelesege, okomultikulti nelkul nincs alkotmany, <br>ezt latni kell. Amig nincs irasban, hogy az egereszolyvnek nincs joga <br>kihalni, addig sorry, fiuk, nincs alaptorveny.<br><br>Sajat korabbi nyilatkozatahoz kepest oszintebben nyilvanult meg <br>Kosane Kovacs Magda alelnok, aki korabban valami "kommunikacios <br>zavarral" magyarazta, hogy az informacios robbanas koraban miert <br>nem jutott el a szocialista kormanytagokhoz az a hir, hogy a frakcio<br><br>az otparti megallapodasnak megfeleloen<br><br>tobb napja megszavazta a koncepciot. KoKoMa most kimondta: egy <br>partnak a "politikai ertekeit es erdekeit" is "megfelelo sullyal" kell <br>kepviselnie a valasztokkal szemben. Na ez az. Szocialis jogok, <br>letbiztonsag kiharcolasa nelkul nincs szocialista part. Az MSZP <br>alelnoke jol latja, hogy partjanak, ha mar nem demokratikus <br>szocializmusban, higitott bernsteinizmusban, felvizezett renegat <br>kautskyanus gezemiceben, hanem piacgazdasagra emlekezteto <br>valamiben utazik, legalabb a szocialis jogokert valo kuzdes latszatat <br>illik produkalnia, ha mar napi szinten learulozzak, amiert nem <br>3,60ert adja a kenyeret es nem garantalja alanyi jogon az elso nohoz <br>jutast. Amugy meg: partprogramot az alkotmanyba! Forza Lenin!<br><br>Az MSZP bajban van, mert a sajat maga altal kitermelt klientura <br>szamara valami identitast kell elobbutobb felmutatnia, mert eddig <br>volt a megszoritas meg a leepites, viszont lassan kozeleg '98, es <br>barmikor megkerdezhetik tole, mondd, MSZP, mire fol olyan nagy a <br>szad, es akkor a vegen meg azt kell mondania: azert, hogy jobban <br>bekaphassam. A nagyobbik kormanypart identitasa azonban  <br>szogezzuk le  kifejezetten maganugy, amit nem rendelhet ala az <br>alkotmanyozasnak. Ha ezt teszi, ha a szocialista miniszterek (plusz a <br>gyori programjat bonyolito Horn Gyula) keresztbe tesznek sajat <br>partjuknak, ha a demokracia csak ugyrendi, nem pedig politikai <br>kerdes, akkor inkabb feudalismonarchikus allapotban elunk, mint <br>polgari demokraciaban.<br><br>Ez az alkotmanykoncepcio a legjobb volt, amit ez a nyuves orszag <br>eddigi szanalomra melto tortenete soran latott. Eltorolte az altalanos <br>hadkotelezettseget, a magyar jogtortenetben eloszor, nehany szaz <br>eves kesessel alkotmanyos alapra helyezte a Habeas Corpust (a 72 <br>oran tuli fogva tartas eseten vademelesi kotelezettseget irva elo az <br>ugyesznek), beemelte az alkotmanyossag egyetemes elveit a <br>szabadsag, egyenloseg es testveriseg alapjan. Ez utobbi ironiaja, hogy <br>meg a liberalisok sem gondoltak a konzervativ ellenallason <br>atvihetonek a francia forradalmi harmas jelszo beiktatasat a <br>szovegbe; aztan a keresztenydemokratak (Gaspar M., Isepy, <br>Rubovszky, Varga L.), miutan elvetettek egy kodos, szeretetrol, <br>turelemrol, megertesrol, szolidaritasrol valo javaslatukat, zavarukban <br>frigiai sapkat oltottek.<br><br>Nem a bolsevik partfegyelmet kell szamon kerni az MSZP vezetoin, <br>hanem tobbek kozott azt a minimalis erkolcsi erzeket, amelybol <br>kiindulva nem hosszu honapok utan, utolag vetoznak nekik nem <br>tetszo ugyekben, hanem esetleg idoben szolnak, ha mondjuk meg a <br>sztrajkjogot benyomatnak. Vegyuk peldaul Vastagh Palt. O <br>Magyarorszagon az igazsagugyminiszter. Vastagh Pal nem az a <br>szoszatyar ember. Ha valami gondja van, nem szol, inkabb magaba <br>fojt, kivar, eljon a gombnyomas napja, akkor viszont lecsap, mint tot <br>az adobeszedore. De az, hogy a partvezetes es a kormanytagok <br>bohocot csinalnak a partbol, a koalicios partnerbol, es ami ennel <br>sokkal sulyosabb: az egesz magyar parlamentarizmusbol, raadasul <br>sumakul, abban remenykedve, hogy majd elkenodik a turpissag, <br>mint orr alatt leheletnyi takony, s pusztan azert, mert ezt olvastak <br>egy alsoklagenfurti politologia docens husz ev elotti dolgozataban a <br>mussolinista osztrak Sozialpartnerschaftrol, az azert tenyleg botrany, <br>meg egy ilyen hihetetlenul magas ingerkuszobu orszagban is.<br><br>Hetfon a Nepszabadsag cimlapsztorija ez volt: "Vezereink ismet a <br>helyukon vannak". Igy igaz, enne meg a fene.<br><br>==<br><br>[Lovas Istvant es a Demokratat tamado liberalbolsevik cikk]<br><br>I. KOZEPKELET<br><br> Valaki folhivott. Annyira osszeismerkedtunk telefonon, hogy <br>bizalmas titkot meselt el nekem. Azt, hogy mi tortent a Demokrata <br>szerkesztosegenek legutobbi lapindito ertekezleten. Eleg az hozza, <br>mondta, hogy egy torokbol sikkantgattak es hejehujaztak, amikor <br>Lovas Istvan csillogo szemekkel, egesz testen vegigremego adaz <br>izgalommal bejelentette: magat Jancso Miklost kapta el! Donto <br>bizonyitekot talalt arra, hogy valaha antiszemita volt. Cserkesz <br>koraban!  Na jo...  emelte fol az ujjat Bencsik Andras, a foszerkeszto, <br>aki a hetvenes evekben a legremenykeltobb iro volt am ebben az <br>orszagban.  Najo, de eddig azt bizonygattuk, hogy a cserkeszet nem <br>volt antiszemita.<br><br>Ez senkinek nem jut majd eszebe -  mondta Lovas, a hazai es <br>nemzetkozi, valamint a csillagkozi zsidosag zsigeri kutatoja.<br><br>Es hiteles szemely az, aki elmondta? - kerdezte Bencsik.<br><br>Hogyne! Valaki folhivott telefonon- de azota fenykepet is kuldott <br>magarol! , es szepen belemondta, hogy egyreszt Jancso Miklos roman, <br>valojaban egy Nyiku, masreszt egy bizonyos Hargitai Ocsinek azt <br>mondta, hogy "itt nincs helye zsido fattyunak". Plusz meg azt is <br>enekelte nyikhaj koraban ez a Nyiku, hogy "Horthy Miklos katonaja <br>vagyok".<br><br>Nincs ennek az Ocsinek valami rendes neve?<br><br>Elfelejtettem megkerdezni mondta Lovas, a kurator, a tanacsado, az <br>alnevzsonglor, a vidam foljelento.<br><br>Es van ezen a fenykepes emberen kivul, aki emlekszik ezekre a <br>dolgokra?<br><br>Az az ember a telefonba azt nyilatkozta, hogy "konnyen meglehet".<br><br>Akkorjo... szorul a Charta token a hurok. Nem telefonalhatna a jovo <br>heten valaki, hogy Farkashazy kislanyokat ronditott meg?<br><br>Rontott. De kisfiuk jobbak lennenek. Zsido kolykok.<br><br>Bocsanat, hogy kozbebeszelek... - mondta a tole megszokott halk <br>felenkseggel Sesztak Agnes, a foszerkeszto helyettese, aki azelott a <br>Magyar Ujsagirok Orszagos Szovetsege etikai bizottsaganak <br>csakugyan kivalo tagja volt.<br><br>Ezek ugye olyan otven eve tortent dolgok. Nem lehet, hogy az a <br>fenykepes bacsi a telefonban nem emlekszik pontosan?<br><br>Tiszta logikarol tett tanubizonysagot, mert azt mondta, hogy Jancso <br>Nyiku azertjelenik meg hol cserkeszsuvegben, hol leninsapkaban, hol <br>meg sabeszdekliben, mert a penznek nincs szaga.<br><br>Biztos, hogy nem azert, mert peldaul egy zsido szertartason illik <br>fejfedot venni? Ugye, Clinton elnok se zsido, Kohl kancellar plane <br>nem, aztan Rabin temetesen megis sabeszdeklit viseltek.<br><br>Na jo, hat ha allandoan kukacoskodunk, akkor nem lehet ujsagot <br>csinalni! - kialtott Lovas, aki a szakma egyontetu velemenye szerint a <br>haza egyik legkedvesebb es legokosabb ujsagiroja. Foljelento <br>hajlamat is megbocsatja mindenki: aristomban toltott idejenek tudjak <br>be. Neha idegi alapon van.<br><br>Nem lehetne esetleg megkerdezni Jancso Miklost, ugye etikailag ugy <br>illik. Vagy esetleg szembesiteni ezzel a... Ugye, megiscsak furcsa, hogy <br>Jancso eleg regota vilaghiru, eleg regota lehet barkirol barmit <br>mondani, de pont most jut eszebe ez a zsidofattyus tortenet.<br><br>Ha sokat tokolunk, lelovi a te mat a Magyar Forum vagy az Uj <br>Magyarorszag.<br><br>Nincs tobb kerdesem - mondta szomoruan Sesztak Agnes.<br><br>Akkor viszont jol elo kell kesziteni a temat. Kerete is legyen neki! - <br>mondta Bencsik.<br><br>A szokasosnal tobbet ne zsidozzunk. En majd a vezercikkemben <br>megemlitem, hogy el kell kuldeni Izraelbe a FarkashazyJancso <br>kommandot. Majd jol kinevettetem oket, hogy milyen gyavak. <br>Mindenkeppen betesszuk Monus Aron konyvenek hirdeteset, aztan A <br>kommunista part es a zsidosag cimu konyvet, meg esetleg valamit <br>Pokol Belatol, mert abban nyilvan ir a zsido mediahidrarol...<br><br>Lesz egy tanulmany a magyar polgarosodasrol. Nem nagyon <br>zsidozunk benne, de hangulatkelto elemkent a folhalmozok kozott jol <br>jon majd par nev: Heller, Klein, Strasser, Gutthmann... - vetette kozbe <br>valaki, de nem tudom ki, mert nem is voltam ott.<br><br>Ezutan johetne Jancso Nyikuka esete. Aztan egy nagyon jo kis <br>osszeallitas az SZDSZ egyhazarol, a Hit Gyulekezeterol. A Jerusalem <br>Post kulon mellekletben, nyolc teljes oldalon foglalkozott az izraeli <br>latogatasukkal. Meg van itt egy nagyon zavaros konyv a Hit <br>Gyulekezete kiadasaban. Az a cime, hogy Az "egyhaz" es a zsidosag <br>tragikus tortenete. Ebbol idezhetnenk lazitaskeppen. Es akkor meg a <br>lapszemlebe belekerulhetne a Corriere delta Sera cikke, amely bol <br>kiderul, hogy Izraelben allitolag gyanus korulmenyek kozott <br>elpusztult egy csomo jemeni gyerek.<br><br>A lap vegen pedig egy interjuban Grandpierre K. Endre megemliti <br>majd, hogy Magyarorszag legvegzetesebb baja az, hogy ezer <br>esztendeje idegen uralom alatt all kozolte mondjuk az egeszsegugyi <br>rovat vezetoje.<br><br>Hat akkor ennyi - mondta a foszerkeszto. De mielott a munkatarsak <br>folalltak volna, meg elmerengve hozzatette:<br><br>Tudjatok, valamikor a hetvenes evekben egyszer kint voltam a <br>Szovjetunioban. Follapoztam a karpataljai magyar ujsagokat, es azt <br>ereztem, hogy a halal nez ki beloluk. Akkor hataroztam el: ha egyszer <br>majd lapot csinalok, barmit erezhet az olvaso, ha kinyitja, csak ezt <br>nem.<br><br>Andrassew & Tettamanti<br><br>==<br><br>[Lovas Istvant tamado cikk a Magyar Hirlapban melyre valo valasz <br>megjelent mar a Nemzetben megjelent]<br><br>FARAGO VILMOS <br><br>Ket kulcsmondat ki alkalmat kinalt az itt kovetkezok elmondasahoz, a <br>A jobboldalinak mondott ujsagirok egyike. Eleterol vajmi keveset <br>tudok, de eppen ez a keves szolgal mondandom alapjaul: hazank <br>napnyugati hataran tul elt evtizedeken at, volt a muncheni Szabad <br>Europa Radio munkatarsa is, itthon a fordulat utan turit fel. Cikkei es <br>a rola elterjedt hirek alapjan diabolikus jelensegnek kepzelhetnenk. <br>Holott valoszinu, hogy olyan amber, mint barki mas. De ha irni kezd, <br>valami irtozatos serelem vezeti a kezet. Ki bantja'? A radio Vasarnapi <br>Ujsagjaban arrol kerdeztek, vane most sajtoszabadsag <br>Magyarorszagon. Azt valaszolta hogy nincs, es ehhez meg elfogultnak <br>sem kellett lennie. Ehhez lehet valaki jobboldali is, baloldali is. A <br>sajtoszabadsag tudnullik csakugyan hibadzik, ez valahogy a dolog <br>termeszete. Hol a politika urai korlatoznak ben unket, hol a penz urai; <br>kulonbseg csak a korlatozas mertekeben es modszereiben lehet. Ha a <br>mertek csekely, a modszerek kifinomultak, tamadhat annak illuzioja <br>is, hogy szabadsag van. Nalunk most, senkinek sincs ilyen illuzioja. Es <br>vitaja sincs ekorul senkinek a radioban megkerdezett kollegaval. De <br>valaszaban volt egy erdekes mondat. Kulcsmondat, ha ugy tetszik, <br>mert valasz nyerheto segitsegevel egy mentalitas magyarazatara. <br>Eorsi Istvant kezdte emlegetni, aki lam, ugyancsak bevallja <br>oszintesegi rohamaban a sajtoszabadsag serelmet, majdjott az a <br>bizonyos mondat, melyet nem szo szerint, de remelem, lenyege <br>szerint idezek: "Mert fura gondolatok tamadhatnak - mondta Eorsirol <br>- olyan ember fejeben is, aki itthon elte at a Kadarkorszak evtizedeit, <br>ezert atitatta ot e korszak szellemisege." Ezt mondta napnyugatrol <br>hazatert kollegank s hogy epp a demokratikus ellenzekiek kozt is <br>gerillaharcosnak szamito Eorsi volna az, akit olyan nagyon atitatott a <br>Kadarkorszak szellemisege es nem mi tobbiek, koztunk is a volt <br>muzeumigazgatok, vendeglatoipari vezerek meg tervhivatali <br>osztalyvezetok igencsak kerdeses ugyan, de altalaban igaz, hogy aki <br>sokaig el egy politikai kozegben, hasonul hozza. Az ellenzeki es <br>disszidens orosz iro a Parizsban elo Goncourtdijas Andrei Makine epp <br>most mondta a Magyar Televizioban: o meg mindig szovjet <br>mentalitasu keleturopai ertelmiseginek erzi magat.         <br><br>Am, ha a Kelet embereire igaz ez igaznak kell lennie a napnyugat <br>embereire is. Mondom tehat az en kulcsmondatomat: "Indulatos <br>kollegankban fura gondolatok tamadhatnak, mert nem itthon         <br>alte at a Kadarkorszak evtizedeit, ezert atitatta ot egy a mienke         <br>tol kulonbozo szellemiseg." Es ezzel kenyes kerdeshez erkeztem.         <br>Igy hangzik: azoknak a magyar honfitarsainknak akik nem a ha         <br>zaban es nem velunk eltek at az elmult evtizedeket van e vagy nem         <br>joguk, mert az persze hogy van kompetenciajuk ahhoz, hogy ite         <br>letet mondjanak rolunk? Minthogy nem erezhetik at ami szamunkra <br>termeszetes, erthetike egyaltalan? Az ember folyton valaszt: mit <br>fogad el, mit nem. De a kfnalat sohasem tisztan fekete feher. <br>Elfogadom 1970ben, amit a hatalom a civilizalodasert tesz,  a kultura <br>tamogatasaert, a nepjoletert. De nem fogadom el a , tipusterves" <br>civilizaciot, a kultura politikailag szelektalt tamogatasat, a nepjoleti <br>intezkedesek magatt a lekenyerezo szandekot. Erti ezt, aki merev <br>kommunizmus- antikommunizmus kategoriakban  gondolkodik'? <br>Szemrehanyasokat kapok egy berni magyartol,  miert partoltam <br>annak ideien Kadar Janost egy vitaban. A szemrehanyast rossz helyre <br>cimezi, alighanem egyik nevrokonommal teveszt ossze. De ha <br>partoltam volna Kadar Janost? Mondjuk Erich Honeckerrel, Gustav <br>Husakkal vagy Ceausescuval szemben? Ha vedtem volna a <br>jarhatobbnak igerkezo magyar kulonutal? Erti ezt a nem is csekely <br>disztinkciot, akinek egyik kutya, masik eb'? Meg az igazan joindulatu <br>Habsburg Otto is azt irta, epp e hasabokon, hogy csak azt vettek fel <br>nalunk egyetemre, aki belepett a partba. Hogy Rakosiek idejeben <br>nem kotelessegnek,  hanem kituntetesnek szamitott, Kadarek <br>idejeben meg egyre kevesbe szamitott: parttage az egyetemre <br>jelentkezo vagy sem'? Lehet hogy ezt is csak mi kozvetlen reszesek <br>tudjuk?   Csakhogy akkor kollegank indulatainak alkatan tuli egyik le         <br>hetseges forrasa az ismerethiany. Nem tudja, kik vagyunk. mive         <br>formaltak bennunket viszonyaink, milyenne formaltuk mi a viszo         <br>nyainkat. Hogyan hasonultunk hozzajuk, hogyan hasonitottuk         <br>oket hozzank. Szeretne, ha olyanok volnank, mint o, es luhos,         <br>hogy masmilyenek vagyunk. Ki bantja tehat'.' Mi bantjuk. A mi         <br>massagunk bantja. Ez az, amit irtozatos serelemkent el at most.         <br>Mit tehetnenk az erdekeben, hiszen kar volna verbalis tehetse         <br>get serelmi szozuhatagokba fullasztania. Tanacsot adhatunk neki.         <br>Figyeljen minket tovabb, kritikai figyelemmel termeszetesen, de a         <br>megfigyelo poziciojabol fakado empatiaval is. Ha aztan en majd         <br>valamelyest bennunket, ne tegyen ugy, mint nemely sorstarsaink,         <br>akik elhatarozott amneziajukban ugy viselkeinek, mintha soha         <br>sem igyekeztek volna jelesre vizsgazni mnrxizmusbol, mintha nem         <br>enekeltek volna mozgalmi dalt nyari taborozason, vagy nem vo         <br>nultak volna fel Kadar Janos elott majus elsejen. Erezzen is ve         <br>lunk tehat, sot valamelyest hasonuljon hozzank.         <br><br>Mi vagyunk tobben.<br><br>==<br><br>OMRI orosz valasztasi analizis<br><br>FIRST LADY: YELTSIN HAS A COLD. Rumors continue to circulate that <br>President Boris Yeltsin is seriously ill, but, appearing on NTV on 4 <br>July, Naina Yeltsin said her husband merely needs rest to recover <br>from a cold. She noted that Yeltsin is not "superhuman," and even the <br>young people on his staff have been exhausted by the schedule he <br>has kept over the last four months, when he has slept no more than <br>four hours a night.  Laura Belin in Moscow<br><br>CHERNOMYRDIN SKEPTICAL ABOUT COALITION GOVERNMENT... <br>Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin told journalists on 4 July that <br>"there is no talk of any sort of coalition government," ITARTASS <br>reported. While rejecting the idea of a coalition government formed <br>on a political basis, he confirmed that professionals of various <br>political stripes will be invited to join the new cabinet. When asked, <br>he did not exclude the possibility that Gennadii Zyuganov might be <br>offered a portfolio. He stressed that the future government must be <br>united. "No matter what color people were when they join the <br>government, they must all have one color working," the prime <br>minister added. Since taking office in December 1992, Chernomyrdin <br>has generally been viewed as a balancing force in the cabinet.  Laura <br>Belin in Moscow<br><br>-WARNS OFF LEBED... Chernomyrdin also said that the post of vice <br>president can only be introduced if the Constitution is amended, and <br>underlined that "a candidate for this post must be chosen in <br>nationwide elections, as is the head of state."  He seemed to be <br>rebuking Aleksandr Lebed, who on 29 June called for the creation of <br>the vice presidency and proposed himself for the job (see OMRI Daily <br>Digest ,1 July 1996).  In response to questioning about the powers of <br>the new Security Council secretary, Chernomyrdin said: "I am not <br>going to delegate any of my powers to anyone." Asked about Lebed's <br>criticism of the "energy barons" (see OMRI Daily Digest, 3 July 1996), <br>the prime minister said: "We must all calm down after the electoral <br>tension, and in the future each person must manage his own affairs, <br>as defined by law."  Peter Rutland<br><br>-BUT WELCOMES THE ELECTION RESULT. Chernomyrdin said he was <br>pleased that "Russians have made their choice for democracy and the <br>stability of the state." "The election convinced all of us, and the whole <br>world, that Russia is a normal, predictable, civilized country." He said <br>that he "bows low before Boris Yeltsin" in recognition of his role. But <br>Chernomyrdin also expressed some frustration with the character of <br>the election campaign. "In future it will not happen that a choice <br>between systems is foisted on us instead of the choice of a <br>president," he said.  Peter Rutland<br><br>BODYGUARD SERVICES MERGED. President Yeltsin signed a decree on <br>2 July merging two services responsible for guarding state officials, <br>the Federal Protection Service (FSO) and the Presidential Security <br>Service (SBP), Russian and Western agencies reported on 4 July. The <br>new body will be called the State Protection Service (GSO). The SBP <br>had been headed by Yeltsin's close confidante Aleksandr Korzhakov <br>until the latter was fired on 20 June along with three other key <br>hardliners. Yurii Krapivin, FSO head, was appointed acting chief of <br>the SBP in his place. Under Korzhakov, the SBP amassed considerable <br>powers, including the right to supervise the FSO. Previously, <br>however, the State Protection Administration (GUO), the predecessor <br>to the FSO, had been in charge of the SBP. Thus, the most recent <br>change marks a return to the old situation. Under the Law on <br>Protection, signed by Yeltsin in May, the president has the right to <br>reorganize the bodyguard services.  Penny Morvant<br><br>POSTELECTION PERSONNEL CHANGES IN THE OFFING? Izvestiya on 5 <br>July reported that changes are expected in the president's staff. <br>Presidential adviser Georgii Satarov said the staff will be <br>strengthened by professionals and hinted that changes will affect <br>several key officials. Citing information from an unnamed Kremlin <br>official,  the article contended that Chief of Staff Nikolai Yegorov will <br>lose his job. The paper  argued that Yeltsin's personnel policy will be <br>heavily influenced by the "Lebed factor,"  as his presence in the <br>Kremlin will require "serious cadre counterweights." Meanwhile, <br>Viktor Ilyushin, Yeltsin's first aide, said on 4 July he believes the <br>president's election headquarters will not be disbanded.  Asked <br>about former First Deputy Prime Minister Anatolii Chubais, Ilyushin <br>was equivocal, saying only that it had been very interesting to work <br>with Chubais. It has been rumored that Ilyushin himself, who went <br>on leave during the campaign to work at the election headquarters, <br>may not return to the post of first aide.   Penny Morvant<br><br>YAVLINSKII ANGLES FOR CABINET POST... Yabloko leader Grigorii <br>Yavlinskii suggested on 4 July that he would accept the post of first <br>deputy prime minister in charge of economic policyif President <br>Yeltsin agrees to pursue a liberal economic policy, to respect human <br>rights in domestic and foreign policy, and to end the war in <br>Chechnya, Russian media reported on 4 July. However, Yavlinskii has <br>as yet not been offered any cabinet portfolio, and his behavior <br>between the rounds may work against him. Yavlinskii refused to <br>endorse Yeltsin directly and unconditionally. Instead he asked his <br>supporters not to vote for a communist and not to vote against both <br>candidates. Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin responded with <br>sarcasm when asked on 4 July whether Yavlinskii might join the <br>government. "I don't understand what Yavlinskii has to do with <br>anything... Can someone tell me, has he done something?...The <br>government must be made up of responsible people" he said.  Laura <br>Belin in Moscow<br><br>-AS DO OTHER OPPOSITION POLITICIANS. Agrarian Party of Russia <br>(APR) leader Mikhail Lapshin suggested that his party would be <br>interested in holding certain cabinet posts concerned with the <br>agroindustrial complex, ORT reported on 4 July. Last year two cabinet <br>ministers were highranking APR members, but Agriculture Minister <br>Aleksandr Nazarchuk was sacked in a January cabinet reshuffle, and <br>the APR expelled Deputy Prime Minister Aleksandr Zaveryukha after <br>he helped draft a March presidential decree affirming the private <br>ownership of farmland. Also on 4 July, Vladimir Zhirinovsky <br>announced that he might consider accepting the post of Foreign <br>Minister, Interior Minister, or Justice Minister all portfolios he is <br>certain not to be offered, ORT reported. At a 28 June press <br>conference, Zhirinovsky said that his Liberal Democratic Party of <br>Russia would not accept any cabinet positions and would "constantly <br>criticize" both the president and government after the election.  <br>Laura Belin in Moscow<br><br>ZYUGANOV ACKNOWLEDGES YELTSIN VICTORY. Communist leader <br>Gennadii Zyuganov on 4 July conceded victory to Yeltsin, saying he <br>would respect the will of Russian citizens, Russian and Western <br>agencies reported. He said that "given the conditions we faced, we got <br>a good result." Zyuganov repeated the charge that he had had little <br>chance of victory given the media bias in favor of Yeltsin and the <br>Kremlin's "unprecedented mobilization of state funds." He claimed <br>that there had been "crude violations" of the electoral rules and said <br>his party planned to challenge them in court. He again voiced <br>suspicions about the result in Dagestan, where Yeltsin won in the <br>runoff although Zyuganov had taken the most votes in the first <br>round. An early report on NTV on the secondround results in the <br>republic also put Zyuganov in front, with 76%. Zyuganov noted that <br>the 40% of the vote his bloc had won nationwide confirmed its "high <br>social significance," and he reaffirmed his willingness to participate <br>in a coalition government. He concluded that the left opposition, <br>which in three years had developed from "a persecuted and nearly <br>illegal organization to an allRussian political movement," was now <br>established in a twoparty system against the "party of power."  <br>Penny Morvant<br><br>ZYUGANOV DOES SUPRISINGLY BADLY IN CAUCASUS. In a number of <br>areas, communist candidate Zyuganov received a lower percentage of <br>the vote in the second round than he had in the first, according to <br>preliminary results published by the National News Service on the <br>Internet on 4 July. With 97% of the vote counted, Zyuganov was <br>doing surprisingly poorly in several regions in the Caucasus. In <br>KarachaevoCherkessiya, KabardinoBalkariya, and North Ossetiya, he <br>polled up to 10 percentage points less in the second round than he <br>had in the first; turnout was up significantly in all these areas in the <br>runoff although it dropped slightly nationwide. In Dagestan, there <br>was a difference of more than 23 percentage points between the two <br>roundsa result that Zyuganov has publicly queried. In the Volga area, <br>the vote for Zyuganov declined in Mordoviya and Tatarstan. The <br>Communists have appealed the results of the firstround voting in the <br>latter republic in court (see OMRI Daily Digest, 19 June 1996). Yeltsin <br>supporters have contended that vote rigging artificially inflated <br>Zyuganov's backing in these areas in the first round and that more <br>stringent monitoring reduced such abuses in the runoff.  Penny <br>Morvant and Scott Parrish<br><br>YELTSIN INAUGURATION LIKELY IN EARLY AUGUST. Aleksandr <br>Beshnyakov, secretary of the Central Electoral Commission, told <br>ITARTASS on 4 July that the final results of the presidential runoff <br>will not be announced until at least 7 July, and possibly not until 8 or <br>9 July. Since the election law stipulates that a newly elected <br>President be sworn in on the 30th day following the official <br>publication of the election results, that means Yeltsin's inauguration <br>will be held between 7 and 9 August. After meeting with Yeltsin on 4 <br>July, Moscow Mayor Yurii Luzhkov said Yeltsin had decided to hold <br>the inaugural ceremony on 9 August. According to Article 82 of the <br>Russian Constitution, the new president takes the oath of office <br>before the assembled members of the Federation Council, State <br>Duma, and Constitutional Court. As a result, the inauguration will <br>disrupt the usual August recesses of these three bodies.   Scott <br>Parrish<br><br>GOVERNMENT TO SUBMIT RESIGNATIONS TO YELTSIN. The formation <br>of a new government is also likely to interfere with the customary <br>August holidays of Russian parliamentarians. According to Article <br>116 of the Russian Constitution, the incumbent government must <br>resign when a new president is elected. However, the Constitution <br>does not specify exactly when the old government should submit its <br>resignation after the election results are officially announced, or after <br>the new president is sworn in. A federal law regulating this <br>procedure has not yet been adopted. However, officials in the current <br>government have suggested that the government will formally resign <br>following the official publication of the election results. Under Article <br>111 of the Constitution, the president must nominate a candidate for <br>prime minister within two weeks of his inauguration, and the Duma <br>then has one week to approve or reject the nominee. Should the <br>Duma thrice reject the president's candidate, he can dissolve the <br>assembly and call new parliamentary elections. Since Yeltsin will <br>probably not be inaugurated until 9 August, the Duma could easily <br>remain in session until mid August, even if it quickly approves <br>Yeltsin's promised nomination of Viktor Chernomyrdin.  Scott Parrish<br><br>CLINTON HAILS YELTSIN VICTORY. President Clinton hailed Boris <br>Yeltsin's reelection on 4 July, saying that "the Russian people have <br>turned their backs on tyranny," Western agencies reported.  <br>Speaking at an Independence Day ceremony in Maryland, Clinton <br>said a "substantial majority" of Russians had shown they supported <br>"the path of reform." Clinton had unofficially but unambiguously <br>backed Yeltsin's bid for a second term, and a victory by Zyuganov <br>would have dealt him a major foreign policy defeat going into his <br>own campaign for reelection this November. Senator Sam Nunn <br>suggested that now the U.S. and Russia could press ahead with arms <br>control issues like START II and the Chemical Weapons Convention, <br>neither of which have been ratified by the Russian Federal <br>Assembly. However, the communistdominated Duma has <br>reservations about both agreements, especially START II, and <br>Yeltsin's reelection is no guarantee of their ratification. Western <br>European leaders, such as German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who <br>supported Yeltsin even more openly than Clinton, also reacted <br>positively to the election results. Although Yeltsin's win may lead to <br>a brief honeymoon in Russian relations with the West, however, it <br>does not resolve divisions over issues like NATO expansion, nuclear <br>cooperation with Iran, and resolution of the Yugoslav conflict. In fact, <br>now that he no longer needs Western support to bolster his <br>campaign, Yeltsin could possibly take a harsher stance on these <br>matters.  Scott Parrish<br><br>CIS LEADERS REACT TO YELTSIN VICTORY.  Predictably, Russia's <br>neighbors also reacted positively to Yeltsin's victory, as the heads of <br>most CIS states had openly endorsed Yeltsin, fearing Zyuganov's <br>intentions if he became president. ITARTASS reported that Ukrainian <br>President Leonid Kuchma said  the future development of Ukraine <br>had depended on the outcome of the Russian presidential polls, and <br>Yeltsin's victory was a signal that Kyiv should press ahead with <br>economic reform. He did not, however, anticipate any softening of <br>Russia's stance on issues like the Black Sea Fleet. Georgian President <br>Eduard Shevardnadze termed Yeltsin's reelection "a victory for <br>democracy in Russia and all over the world," while the presidents of <br>Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Belarus, Tajikistan, and Moldova also hailed <br>Yeltsin's reelection. Armenian President Levon Ter Petrossyan even <br>said that Yeltsin's victory had "finally liberated the Russian people <br>from Bolshevik obscurantism and the nightmarish inheritance of 70 <br>years of inhuman communist rule."  Scott Parrish<br><br>FOREIGN COMMUNISTS DISMAYED BY ZYUGANOV LOSS. While most of <br>the world heaved a sigh of relief at Yeltsin's victory, some communist <br>countries and parties were displeased by Zyuganov's defeat, Western <br>agencies reported on 4 July. Cuban Foreign Ministry spokesman <br>Miguel Alfonso indirectly indicated his government's stance by <br>refusing to comment on the results of the election, terming it an <br>internal Russian affair. The South African Communist Party, which <br>benefited from Soviet support during the struggle against apartheid,  <br>issued a statement which "noted with regret" Zyuganov's loss, and <br>attributed Yeltsin's victory to "fear, confusion, and uncertainty." <br>China at first issued a studiously neutral but somewhat cool <br>statement, saying it "respected the choice of the Russian people," and <br>hoped for the development of a partnership based on equality.  <br>Later, however, Chinese President Jiang Zemin congratulated Yeltsin <br>on his victory, and also praised the Russian president for "giving a <br>direct and powerful impetus" to the development of bilateral ties.  <br>Scott Parrish<br><br>MEDIA MONITORS: ELECTION A STEP BACKWARD. Biased media <br>coverage of the 1996 presidential election "marred the fairness of <br>the democratic process," according to a report issued on 4 July by the <br>European Institute of the Media (EIM), which monitored campaign <br>coverage on behalf of the European Union. The report said that, <br>compared to the 1991 presidential election and parliamentary votes <br>of 1993 and 1995, "candidates were less free to get their views <br>across and voters were given less information of a professional and <br>objective nature." Although the regulatory framework for media <br>coverage in principle guaranteed fair treatment of all candidates, in <br>practice reporting was heavily slanted toward President Yeltsin and <br>against other candidates (with the exception of Aleksandr Lebed), <br>especially Yeltsin's main rival Gennadii Zyuganov. The report devotes <br>special attention to Russia's three main television networks staterun <br>ORT and RTR, and the private network NTV. It attributes the biased <br>coverage to a combination of factors: government interference, <br>commercial interests, and the voluntary cooperation of journalists <br>who wished to prevent a communist return to power.  Laura Belin in <br>Moscow<br><br>MORE PRAISE FOR POLLSTERS... Yevgenii Andryushchenko, the head <br>of sociological services at the Central Electoral Commission, confirmed <br>on 4 July that pollsters had generally been accurate in predicting the <br>outcome of the second round (see also OMRI Special Report, 4 July <br>1996). Andryushchenko said that VCIOM predicted 52% for Yeltsin, <br>close to his actual result of 53.7%, while the Institute of Comparative <br>Social Research (ISSI), the Institute for SocioPolitical Research (ISPI), <br>and the Institute of Sociology of Parliamentarism (ISP), all placed <br>Yeltsin at 5556%. Boris Grushin's Vox Populi was the least accurate of <br>the 10 leading pollsters, predicting 44% for Yeltsin and 31% for <br>Zyuganov.  Peter Rutland<br><br>-AND THE FUTURES MARKET. The futures market did even better <br>than pollsters in predicting the outcome of the second round, Reuters <br>reported on 4 July. On 2 July, the day before the election, the <br>contracts brokers were offering at the Russian Exchange predicted <br>that Yeltsin would win by 52.5% to 42.5%. The actual result was <br>53.7% to 40.4%.  Peter Rutland<br><br>THE VIEW FROM KALMYKIYA On 3 July, the Russian presidential <br>election day, OMRI's Anne Nivat spoke with Kalmyk President Kirsan <br>Ilyumzhinov in Elista, the capital of Kalmykiya. Ilyumzhinov, 31, was <br>elected president of the Autonomous Republic of Kalmykiya (1,500 <br>km south of Moscow, 200 km north of Chechnya) on 15 April, 1993 <br>with more of 70% of the vote. He was reelected president for a <br>further seven years in late 1995. He is also rumored to be a <br>millionaire and one of the wealthiest businessmen in Russia.<br><br>OMRI: Today is election day; what would you tell the voters of <br>Kalmykiya if you went on television today?<br><br>ILYUMZHINOV: When I appeared on television on 13 June, I told <br>them that the President of this Republic, as he is also a citizen of the <br>Russian Federation, had already made his choice to vote for Boris <br>Nikolaevich (Yeltsin). First, because we have to lead the reforms to <br>their end and we have to stress that now, everything is based on the <br>democratic freedom of choice. Second, because we have to go on <br>building a free market; so why should we stop? And third, because <br>my nation, the Kalmyks, suffered a lot in 1943 (when they were <br>deported en masse by Stalin to Siberia), and we stayed in exile for 11 <br>years because of that decision by the communist party. My parents, <br>all the old people, remember it perfectly, so, why should we go <br>backwards? That's why I decided to ask the people of Republic of <br>Kalmykiya to vote for Yeltsin.<br><br>OMRI: But nevertheless, in three districts (raiony) of your Republic <br>the communist candidate Gennadii Zyuganov won a majority in the <br>first round. Is there any specific reason for that vote?<br><br>ILYUMZHINOV: Let's say that it is partly because those three specific <br>regions are places where there is a Russianspeaking majority, <br>whereas everywhere else, people did not forget what happened <br>under the communists in 1943. It's also possible that in those three <br>regions, people forgot how the churches were burned, and how <br>everything was destroyed. And, finally, one cannot exclude the <br>potential influence of Stavropol, the neighbouring Russian region <br>(which voted much more in favor of the communists). The third <br>region concerned in Kalmykiya, in the south, on the Caspian Sea, <br>probably expressed through this vote its disagreement with the way <br>the local politicians work over there; they did not understand that <br>the question is not to choose between Zyuganov or Yeltsin, but to <br>determine our future common way: should we go forwards, stay like <br>we are or go backwards. It is perfectly possible that those people <br>responsible on the very local level did not work very efficiently<br><br>which doesn't mean that I will change them; I have no intention of <br>changing them and nominating others. Anyway, I am sure that they <br>understood that for the second round, it would be more reasonable <br>and worthy to vote for Yeltsin...<br><br>OMRI: In the case of a Zyuganov victory, what would it change for <br>you personally, and for your country?<br><br>ILYUMZHINOV: My future is strongly tied to the future of Kalmykiya, <br>my country which elected me for the second time in November 1995, <br>that's why it wouldn't be positive at all. Indeed, if we again changed <br>the teams, changed our external strategy, our internal politics, it <br>would pose a threat to everything that we have done in the three <br>last years. Three years ago, Kalmykiya was the obscurest part of the <br>Soviet Union and then of the Russian Federation, there was no <br>enterprise here, no cultural life, and within three years, we managed <br>to let people know that here, we don't live in the provinces, we are <br>the same as people in Paris, in Moscow, in Tokyo. Today, we can <br>finally play chess and have fun, and if a new political power comes, I <br>have the bad impression that all those things, like discotheques in <br>the streets, playing chess, etc., would  again be forbidden.<br><br>OMRI: You said in Moscow that in the event of a Zyuganov victory, <br>you would immediately become the first secretary of the communist <br>party in Kalmykiya. Was it a joke?<br><br>ILYUMZHINOV: Yes, I like this kind of humor, I also said that in that <br>case, my republic would become the independant chess republic of <br>Kalmykiya, we could unite with FIDE (the World Chess Federation, <br>whose president is also Kirsan Ilyumzhinov) and create a new state...<br><br>OMRI: How do you react to the serious rumors of voterigging during <br>the first round of the presidential election in your republic ?<br><br>ILYUMZHINOV: Rumors about falsification of the vote exist in this <br>world since the very first vote took place under the Roman Empire. <br>Such rumors will persist as long as elections exist, and as long as <br>there will be losers. Because the loser is never happy about the <br>result and the entire process of losing.<br><br>This material was reprinted with permission of the Open Media          <br>Research Institute, a nonprofit organization with research offices in          <br>Prague, Czech Republic. For more information on OMRI publications,          <br>please write to:  info@omri.cz<br>
</DOC>
